        "Tafseer": "1. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nSad. By the Qur'an containing the reminder (1)\n\n'Sad' is from among the abbreviated letters (Hurufe Muqatta'at). This is the Qur'anic name of this Surah; a comprehensive discussion on these letters has passed at the beginning of Surah Al-Baqarah. Some people have tried to determine its meaning, but in our view, this is merely an affectation.\n\nSome Aspects of the Qur'an Being Designated as a 'Reminder'\n\n'And by the Qur'an containing the reminder' (Wal-Qur'ani dhi-dhikr): Just as the oath of the Qur'an has occurred in Surah Ya-Sin with the attribute 'wise' (Al-Hakeem), similarly here, it has occurred with the attribute 'containing the reminder' (dhi-dhikr). The basic meaning of 'dhikr' is to remind. The Qur'an is entirely a reminder. For this reason, its name has also occurred in various places as 'Dhikr' (reminder). Below in verse 8, this very name has occurred for it. There are several aspects to its being designated by this name and characterized by this attribute:\n\n* It reminds of all those realities which are imbued within human nature but which man has forgotten.\n\n* It also reminds of that guidance which Allah Almighty sent down for creation through His messengers, and which people had forgotten.\n\n* It also informs of that end which those who denied the messengers had to face.\n\n* It also reminds of that stage of account, reckoning, reward, and punishment which people have to face after this worldly life.\n\nAll of these aspects are present within its attribute of 'dhi-dhikr'. Below, under verses 8–17, 46–49, and 86 of this Surah, their explanation is coming.\n\nWhat is Sworn to Is Implied within the Oath\n\nThe statement sworn to (the maqsam 'alayh) of this oath is not mentioned here in words, but is rather implied within the oath itself. This method is adopted in those places where the nature of the oath is such that the statement sworn to is clear from it without being mentioned. Such is the case here; the objective is that the reminders with which the Qur'an is filled are witnesses to the fact that those matters of which the Qurysah are being reminded today are entirely undeniable. If they are not accepting them, the cause is not that there is any room for doubt or suspicion within the Qur'an, but its cause is merely their arrogance and hostility."
