        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 2,
        "Tafseer": "\"But those who disbelieve are in pride and dissension.\" (2)\n\nThe Actual Cause of Opposing the Qur'an\n\n'Those who disbelieve' (alladhina kafaroo) refers here specifically to the Quraysh. It states that the cause of their denial is not that there is any deficiency in the Qur'an's reminding, but rather that they are caught in arrogance and hostility. The explanation of this arrogance and stubbornness of theirs is coming in the subsequent verses. The meaning is that the fault lies not in the Qur'an, but within these people themselves. This Qur'an is performing a highly reasoned, heart-touching, and effective reminding from every aspect, but upon those who have adopted the path of arrogance and opposition, how can its reminding be effective!"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 3,
        "Tafseer": "\"How many a generation have We destroyed before them, and they called out when it was not a time of escape.\" (3)\n\nA Pointer toward the Nations of the Past\n\nThat is, it is highly painful to their arrogance that they are being warned: if they remain firm on denying the Qur'an, they will fall under the grasp of God's punishment. Whereas, many examples of those destroyed before them have been made in history; when nations showed stubbornness like them, We destroyed them. When they were seized in God's grasp, they cried out and proclaimed repentance and faith. But at that time, no way of escape remained for them, because after the manifestation of the punishment, the time for repentance and faith has passed.\n\n'Lata'\n\n'Lata' is originally 'la' (not), but the letter 'ta' has been added to it; similar additions also occur with 'thumma' (then) and 'rubba' (perhaps). However, in this form, it becomes specific to the negation of time, as is the case here."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 4,
        "Tafseer": "\"And they wonder that there has come to them a warner from among themselves. And the disbelievers say, 'This is a magician and a liar.'\" (4)\n\nThe Arrogance of the Deniers\n\nThat is, they wondered that a person from among themselves has come to them as a warner from God. They thought: if God had to send a warner, He would send some superhuman being; what is the sense in making a human like themselves a warner! And if He had to make a human a warner, why did His eye fall upon a poor man; why did He not choose one of the chiefs of Makkah or Ta'if for this purpose? Thus, the Prophet's being human became a cause of denial for them, as did his poverty and lack of wealth. In this verse, the first cause of denial is pointed to. Below in verse 8, the second cause of denial is mentioned, and both of these matters are included in pride and arrogance, which was mentioned above with the word 'Izzat' (pride).\n\nA Slander Devised by the Leaders of the Quraysh to Turn the Common People away from the Qur'an\n\n'And the disbelievers say, \"This is a magician and a liar\"'—meaning, on the basis of this wonder and arrogance of theirs, these disbelievers declared our Prophet to be a magician and a liar. We have explained the reason for their calling the Prophet (pbuh) a magician and the Qur'an magic—stating that although it was impossible for the Quraysh to deny the miraculous eloquence of the Qur'an, they did not want to let their common people be influenced and accept it as the word of God. To save people from this, they called the Qur'an magic and the Prophet (pbuh) a magician, trying to convince people: 'the influence and sway which is in this person's speech is not because revelation descends upon him from the sky, but he is a magician of words; for this reason, his words affect hearts.' The reason for calling the Qur'an poetry and the Prophet (pbuh) a poet was also the same.\n\n'Kadh-dhab' means a liar and a boaster. They uttered this word in the heat of denying the Prophet's (pbuh) claim to prophethood—meaning: this person is indeed a magician of words, but to overawe the common people, he claims that whatever he is reciting to the people is revealed to him from God and that he has come as a warner from God. Since their primary conflict was with the Prophet's (pbuh) claim to prophethood, they were highly severe in its denial, which is also manifest from this word.\n\nThe style of this verse is witness that it contains an expression of regret over the state of these unfortunate people. That is: Allah Almighty sent a warner among them for their warning and reminding, and sent down a Book of reminding for them, but they, out of arrogance, are wondering that a human like themselves has come as a warner; in this arrogance, these disbelievers declared the messenger of Allah to be a magician and a liar."
