        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 7,
        "Tafseer": "\"We have not heard of this in the latest religion. This is not but a fabrication.\" (7)\n\nThe Difference in the Perspectives of the Qur'an and the Quraysh Regarding Arab History\n\nThis is a denial by the Quraysh of that history of the Arab nation which the Prophet (pbuh) narrated. You clarified from the history of all prophets from Hazrat Nuh (peace be upon him) to Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him) and subsequent prophets that all of them taught pure Tawhid. Particularly, the history of Hazrat Ibrahim's (peace be upon him) and Hazrat Ismail's invitation, and of the Ka'bah, which has been described in the Qur'an with great clarity, was meant to clarify to the Arabs that the actual history of their nation begins with Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him) and Hazrat Ismail, and these great prophets had settled their progeny in this land for the service of Islam and the invitation to pure Tawhid, and had constructed this House, of which the Quraysh are the guardians today, for this very purpose. This history was a severe blow to all the assumptions of the Quraysh, but it was so clear and heart-touching that it could appeal to the people; but they, out of their pride and defiance, were not ready to accept it, because of which they said: 'We have not heard this word of Tawhid in the latest period of our nation; therefore, this entire story narrated to us in favor of Tawhid is entirely fabricated.' Their meaning was: if the history of the Arab nation had been what is described in the Qur'an, and which Muhammad (pbuh) is presenting with this challenge, then some echo of it must have been present in the latest period of this nation as well! But we have not heard any such thing from our ancestors. We found this very religion from them, are walking upon it, and will continue walking upon it.\n\nSome have interpreted 'the latest religion' (Al-Millat al-Akhirah) as the Christian religion, but there is no context for this here. The mention of the Christian religion would have been credible and effective for them only if they and their common people had believed in it, or if the Prophet (pbuh) had presented the invitation of Tawhid on the basis of the Christian religion."
