        "AyahNumber": 12,
        "Tafseer": "\"The people of Noah denied before them, and 'Aad and Pharaoh, the owner of stakes,\" (12)\n\nThe Owner of Stakes\n\n'Dhu-l-awtad' literally means the owner of stakes, but in Arabic, stakes are used to refer to tents, and from tents, by way of metaphor, armies are meant. This is a metaphor of the same nature as 'stationary kettles' (qudoor rasiyat) which is used to express someone's generosity; thus, in the Qur'an, this metaphor has occurred for the generosity of Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him). Here, 'Dhu-l-awtad' points to the massive armies of Pharaoh who lived in tents. The abundance of Pharaoh's armies has been mentioned in various places in the Qur'an, and all these armies were drowned in the sea along with him in God's punishment.\n\n'The companions of the thicket' (As-habul-Aykah) refers to the people of Madyan. 'Aykah' means a thicket or forest. It seems that near Madyan there was some thicket; because of this, these people were also known by this name. Its analysis has passed in its proper place.\n\nWhat was stated in verse 11—that when God's punishment comes, no matter how much power and passion a group or nation possesses, it cannot stand against it—is supported by historical proof showing that all these nations denied Allah's messengers, and when His punishment came upon them as a retribution, none of them could stand against it.\n\nIn '[And] those were the companies' ('ula'ikal-ahzab), the predicate (khabar) is omitted, because it is obvious from the context, and the subsequent clause makes it even clearer—implying: see, these were famous nations, but what was their fate! When God's punishment came, they were all blown away like dry wood. The meaning is: the same fate will be yours if you adopt their way."
