    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 17,
        "Tafseer": "2. Subsequent Theme: Verses 17–29\n\nNext, the Prophet (pbuh) is instructed to remain firm on his stance of truth despite all this opposition of his opponents, and to take warning from the story of Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) and also to relate their states to these people—showing that Allah had blessed him with such wealth and power, a tenth of which the Quraysh do not possess, yet upon receiving all this, he did not fall into pride and arrogance like them, but rather as God's favors upon him increased, his gratitude and devotion to Allah also increased. He listened to the disputes of people with great patience and forbearance and made his decisions in accordance with justice, and if during these disputes any matter came before him which was advisory for himself, he immediately fell in prostration of repentance and seek forgiveness of his Lord. Allah gave him a great kingdom which he managed in accordance with His commands. He did not go astray following his desires. He was aware of the reality that those who receive authority in the land and forget the sovereignty of God and the reckoning of the Hereafter will not escape from His grasp. This is because the Creator has not made this world in vain, but rather a Day is necessarily to come in which He rewards those who fulfill the right of His vicegerency in this land, and those who fall into arrogance and create corruption are punished... Recite the verses in this light.\n\n3. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"Be patient over what they say and remember Our servant, David, the possessor of strength; indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah].\" (17)\n\nThe Model of Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) Life is for the Prophet as well as for the Quraysh\n\nThe highly effective events of Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) and Hazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) lives have passed in Surah Al-Anbiya, Surah An-Naml, and Surah Saba. Here, some new events of their lives are described which are a source of consolation for the Prophet (pbuh) and highly advisory for the leaders of the Quraysh, if they benefit from them. The word 'Udhkur' (remember/mention) has two aspects here. One relates to the Prophet (pbuh)—implying: observe patience over these painful words of your opponents, and receive consolation from the life of Our strong servant Dawud—showing how, despite possessing strength and power, he bore the unpleasant attitude of people with great forbearance, made his decisions with justice and mercy, and took warning for his own life from the events of others.\n\nThe second relates to the rebels of the Quraysh—implying: relate the life of Our strong and powerful servant Dawud to these people—showing that although he possessed far greater wealth and power than them, this did not fall them into any pride and arrogance like them; rather, he was a servant who continuously turned to his Lord. The events of his life are witness that he took warning from the events of others, repented over his lapses, and fell in prostration before his Lord.\n\nStrength and Favor are Blessings Only when Accompanied by Devotion\n\n'indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah]': 'Awwab' means one who repeatedly turns to his Lord. The subsequent events are those which highlight this very attribute of Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him). In other places, this attribute is expressed with the words: 'And We gave him Solomon; excellent is the servant; indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah]'.\n\nIt should be kept in mind here that a human is not an angel to be free from committing any mistake. Since man has been blessed with the gift of choice, and his choice is also being tested, at every step there is a possibility of mistake; but Allah Almighty has not placed this possibility of mistake for man's destruction, but this too is a source of achieving the greatest success if he learns to turn to his Lord and repent after his mistake. Man's ruin comes when he commits crime after crime until his crimes so overcome him that let alone being warned himself, if some servant of Allah warns him, he stands up as his enemy out of pride and arrogance. Here, by mentioning both attributes 'the possessor of strength' (dhul-ayd) and 'one who repeatedly turned' (awwab) together, the Qur'an has shown that a strong and powerful person becomes God's close servant only when the attribute of 'awwabiyyah' (turning to Allah) is found within him alongside strength and power. If strength and power produce the arrogance of pride and dissension within him, then this is rebellion and Pharaonism, which is cursed and hated in the sight of Allah."
    },
