    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 20,
        "Tafseer": "\"And We strengthened his kingdom and gave him wisdom and decisive speech.\" (20)\n\nHazrat Dawud's Strength and Power\n\nThis describes Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) strength and power which was mentioned above with the word 'the possessor of strength' (dhul-ayd). 'And We strengthened his kingdom'—meaning We made his kingdom robust, and to keep it robust, We blessed him with the capability of wisdom and decisive speech. Wisdom has been explained in its proper place. 'Decisive speech' (fasl al-khitab) refers to the capability to decide disputes. The word 'khitab' (speech) has occurred below in verse 23 in the sense of dispute and debate. For the robustness of a kingdom, it is necessary that its managers are blessed with the capability of making decisions. If this is absent, the foundation of the kingdom is on sand, even if it possesses an abundance of other resources. This wisdom is achieved through a strong connection with Allah Almighty, without which people prepare the causes of their own destruction. Having the power of government in the hands of such people is like having a sword in the hand of a foolish person."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 21,
        "Tafseer": "\"And has there come to you the news of the adversaries, when they climbed over the wall of the sanctuary?\" (21)\n\nAn Example of Hazrat Dawud's Decisive Speech\n\nThis is an example of their wisdom, their justice, or in the words of the Qur'an, their 'decisive speech' (fasl al-khitab), from which a few matters emerge with great clarity:\n\n* First, in the matter of justice, the rich and the poor were equal in their sight. In their kingdom, even the poorest person could easily obtain their right from the greatest person.\n\n* Second, their subjects had full trust in them. People would reach them for the decision of their affairs without any hesitation—to the extent that if for some reason the guards prevented them, people would sometimes enter by climbing over the wall. They presented their cases with great courage, and he decided their disputes with great forbearance, and was not in the least displeased that people had disrupted his rest, or had not observed manners in addressing him, or had ignored his guards.\n\n* Third, the law of justice in whose light they decided the disputes of others, they also evaluated their own affairs in its light. If even the slightest deviation was felt by them in some corner, they immediately fell in prostration of repentance and sought forgiveness of their Lord... Keeping these basic points in view, now reflect on the individual parts of the actual event.\n\nWith 'And has there come to you' (Hal ataka), the importance of the event is expressed, and in it lies some encouragement for the addressee. The addressee is not necessarily the Prophet (pbuh) alone, but the singular address, as has been explained, also comes for the plural.\n\nThe word 'khasm' (adversary) is used for the parties of a case. It is used identically for both singular and plural.\n\n'when they climbed over the wall of the sanctuary'—'tasawwaroo' means to climb over a wall. According to the rules of Arabic, this word here encompasses the meaning of 'they entered'—meaning: 'they climbed over the walls and entered the sanctuary' (tasawwaroo al-judra wa dakhaloo al-mihrab). 'Mihrab' (sanctuary) can refer to a room of Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) palace or to the palace itself; in Arabic, sometimes the part is mentioned and the whole is meant.\n\nThe Nature of the Event\n\nThe nature of the event seems to be that the two parties of a dispute, along with their companions, tried to present themselves before Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) for a decision at a time which was not for deciding cases, but for rest or worship. At the main gate, the guards must have prevented them from entering the palace at this odd hour, but they did not despair; rather, avoiding the guards' eyes, they entered the palace by climbing over the wall from another side. Climbing over the wall of a great ruler's palace in this manner was a highly severe action, the punishment of which is highly severe in general, but since they had full trust in Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) forbearance, they committed this audacity."
