        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 22,
        "Tafseer": "\"When they entered upon David, and he was terrified of them. They said, 'Fear not. [We are] two adversaries, one of whom has wronged the other, so judge between us with truth and do not exceed [it] and guide us to the sound path.'\" (22)\n\nTheir entering in this manner naturally caused panic to Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him). Thus, he feared that perhaps robbers or his enemies, avoiding the guards' eyes, had entered the palace. But those who entered assured him: 'Fear not, we are not enemies, so do not worry; we are the two parties of a case, one of whom has committed injustice against the other, so judge between us with truth, and do not show any bias or injustice, but guide us to the straight path of justice.'\n\nAlthough their entering was entirely at an odd hour, and the method they adopted was highly inappropriate, and the tone of their address, as is clear from 'do not exceed [it]' (la tushtit), was also highly uncivil, they knew the temperament of their ruler. They knew that no matter how wrong a method they adopted, once they reached Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) and he came to know that they had come seeking justice, He would overlook their audacities and decide their dispute immediately. Thus, their expectation was fully realized. When Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) was assured that these people had come with a case, he immediately turned toward deciding it and did not take any notice of their audacities.\n\nHazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) and Hazrat Umar (ra)\n\nIf you read the life of Hazrat Umar, you will find that the same was the case with him. His door was never closed to the needy. Ordinary people on the street would hold his hand and present their needs with great boldness, and some even with insolence; he listened to them with great forbearance and fulfilled their needs immediately."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 23,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, this is my brother; he has ninety-nine ewes, and I have one ewe; so he said, 'Entrust her to me,' and he overpowered me in speech.\" (23)\n\nThe Details of the Dispute\n\nThis is the detail of the dispute presented by the wronged party. Pointing to the other party, he stated: 'Indeed, this is my brother; he has ninety-nine ewes, and I have only one ewe. He demands that I hand over my ewe to him as well. For this, he disputes with me, and in the dispute, he has overpowered me.'\n\nIt should be kept in mind here that in that era, the primary wealth of that region consisted of sheep and ewes. Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) life before his kingship was spent in sheep-keeping and shepherding. From history, it is even learned that on the coin of that era, the image was of a ewe, and it was called 'na'jah'. Even if this is not correct, this word was well-known in that era to express ownership and wealth.\n\nIn 'and he overpowered me in speech' (wa 'azzani fil-khitab), 'khitab' is in the sense of dispute and debate. Since he was a wealthy man and a wealthy man easily finds supporters, he must have gathered others to his view to suppress the poor man."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 24,
        "Tafseer": "\"He said, 'He has certainly wronged you in demanding your ewe [in addition] to his ewes. And indeed, many partners oppress one another, except those who believe and do righteous deeds - and very few are they.' And David became certain that We had only tried him, so he asked forgiveness of his Lord and fell down bowing and turned [to Him].\" (24)\n\nThe word 'su'al' (asking) here is in the sense of demanding. Its usage in this sense is well-known and has been explained in its proper place. The subsequent preposition 'ila' is an indication that this word here encompasses the meaning of joining or mixing.\n\nHazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) Decision\n\nHazrat Dawud (peace be upon him), upon hearing the case, estimated that the wrong was on the part of the wealthy man, and without any bias, announced his decision: 'He has certainly wronged you in demanding your ewe to mix with his ewes,' and at the same time, made the remark: 'most partners, in their desire to turn their ninety-nine into a hundred, continuously commit injustices against one another. Only those are exempt from this who walk upon the path of faith and righteous deeds, and such people are very few.' The addition of 'ma' with 'qaleel' (very few) produces the meaning of exaggeration.\n\nHazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) Alertness\n\n'And David became certain that We had only tried him, so he asked forgiveness of his Lord and fell down bowing and turned [to Him]': This points to Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) specific attribute of 'awwabiyyah' and 'anabah'—showing that despite being a king, he did not fall into any pride and arrogance like worldly rulers, but was a servant who feared his Lord; because of this, in the light of this event, he immediately evaluated his own affairs and, feeling remorseful over a weakness of his, fell in prostration to seek forgiveness of his Lord.\n\nWhat was this weakness? The Qur'an has not specified it. This matter is a secret between Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) and his Lord; therefore, no one has the right to search or pry into it. From 'that We had only tried him' (annama fatannahu), only this indication emerges: alongside deciding the case, Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) became alert that he himself was caught in a similar trial. If a person is determined to give this trial the shape of an event, keeping Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) states in view, they may assume: just as rulers sometimes have to interfere with others' property for some personal or collective need, Hazrat Dawud also faced some such need; general rulers do not care about anyone in such matters. They can drive a bulldozer over the huts of the poor to make the road to their palace straight, but Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) was a God-fearing king; he could not take any such action, and if any wrong desire had arisen in his heart to interfere with someone's property, he repented of it upon being warned by this event. The primary beauty of an upright person is that he takes warning for himself from the events of others, and if any wrong desire has arisen within him, he seeks forgiveness of his Lord. What emerges from the words of the Qur'an goes at most up to this limit; as for those fabricated stories that are quoted in some commentaries, our prayer regarding them is that Allah Almighty forgive those who committed the act of quoting them in their books.\n\nIn 'and fell down bowing and turned' (wa kharra raki'an wa anab), both bowing and prostration are meant. The mention of bowing is explicit, and 'kharra' (fell down) is a proof of prostration. 'Anaba' points to the turning of the heart. Bowing and prostration are only apparent proofs of turning to God. Their actual spirit is produced by the turning of the heart."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 25,
        "Tafseer": "\"So We forgave him that; and indeed, for him with Us is a near position and a good place of return.\" (25)\n\nRepentance Increases a Person's Rank\n\nFollowing this alertness and seeking of forgiveness of Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him), Allah Almighty forgave his lapse, and since every sincere repentance increases a person's rank and every turning to Allah brings closer proximity, his ranks were increased with Allah."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 26,
        "Tafseer": "\"[We said], 'O David, indeed We have made you a successor upon the earth, so judge between the people with truth and do not follow [your] desire, as it will lead you astray from the way of Allah.' Indeed, those who go astray from the way of Allah will have a severe punishment for having forgotten the Day of Account.\" (26)\n\nInstruction to Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him)\n\nFollowing the aforementioned warning and Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) repentance and seeking of forgiveness, Allah Almighty instructed him in highly clear words: 'O David! We have made you a successor upon the earth by giving you some authority and power, so the requirement of this vicegerency is that you use this authority and power in accordance with the will of your Creator and judge between people with truth and justice, and never follow your desires, as they will lead you astray from the path of truth and justice. Remember constantly that those who deviate from the path of Allah will be caught in a severe punishment for their crime of forgetting the Hereafter.'\n\nThis instruction given to Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) is for all rulers of the world, and indeed for all humans. Whoever receives any authority and power receives it from God, and every person will be held responsible on the Day of Judgment as to whether they used it in accordance with the will of God or followed their desires. Then, whoever ignored this Day of Account to follow their desires will face the end mentioned above."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 27,
        "Tafseer": "\"And We did not create the heaven and the earth and that between them without purpose. That is the assumption of those who disbelieve, so woe to those who disbelieve from the Fire.\" (27)\n\nThe Necessity of the Day of Account\n\nAfter concluding the story of Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him), this is a turn toward the addressees. The reality is clarified before them: why is it necessary that a Day comes in which every person is responsible before their Lord as to whether they used the choice bestowed by God correctly or incorrectly? It states: We have not created this world without purpose, but with truth, and for the manifestation of this truth, We have appointed the Day of Judgment, in which every person will receive the reward for their goodness, and whoever committed evil will face its punishment.\n\n'That is the assumption of those who disbelieve'—meaning those who deny the Hereafter consider this world to be a plaything. In their view, this world is everything, and since in this world it is not necessary that punishment is meted out for evil or reward given for goodness, they assumed that in the sight of its Creator, there is no distinction between goodness and evil. 'so woe to those who disbelieve from the Fire'—it states that those who deny the Hereafter and are indifferent to reward and punishment will face the destruction of the Fire."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 28,
        "Tafseer": "\"Or should We treat those who believe and do righteous deeds like corrupters in the land? Or should We treat those who fear Allah like the wicked?\" (28)\n\nThis is a question by way of wonder—asking: do those who do not believe in the Hereafter and reward and punishment assume that We will make those who adopt faith and righteous deeds equal to those who create corruption in the land, or that Our dealing with those who fear God and the rebellious will be identical? Meaning, the logical consequence of not believing in the Hereafter is this, and this is a thing which cannot be conceived regarding a Wise, Merciful, Powerful, and Exalted God. This same reality has been explained by Lord Masih (peace be upon him) in different styles in the parables of the vineyard—showing: how is it possible that a master appoints his servants to manage his vineyard, some of whom create corruption in his vineyard while others perform their duties with honesty, and the master deals with both identically? If any master does so, it must be accepted that he is either entirely powerless and ignorant or highly foolish and unjust... and both of these are matters from which Allah is entirely pure."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 29,
        "Tafseer": "\"[This is] a blessed Book which We have revealed to you, [O Muhammad], that they might reflect upon its verses and that those of understanding would be reminded.\" (29)\n\nThe Objective of the Qur'an\n\nAddressing the Prophet (pbuh), He stated: We have sent down this Book to you to remind of these realities, and this is a blessed Book which is life-giving for hearts, and the objective of its sending down is that those who possess intellect reflect upon its verses and receive reminding from them. This is a highly great favor of Allah which He has bestowed upon people, provided they value this blessing by abandoning their pride and hostility. This is the repetition of the same theme in other words which passed in the first verse."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 30,
        "Tafseer": "4. Subsequent Theme: Verses 30–40\n\nNext, referring to some events of the life of Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) famous son, Hazrat Sulaiman, it is clarified that he also walked precisely in the footsteps of his father. Allah Almighty blessed him with unparalleled greatness and power, but he did not fall into pride and arrogance to create corruption in the land, but rather whatever step he took, he took fearing his Lord, and if even the slightest lapse occurred on his part, he immediately fell before his Lord in repentance and seeking of forgiveness. These events are also narrated to warn and alert the leaders of the Quraysh... Recite the verses.\n\n5. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"And to David We gave Solomon. Excellent was the servant; indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah].\" (30)\n\nHazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) mention has occurred here in relation to his father Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) in such a way as if he was bestowed upon Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) as a reward for his virtues.\n\nThe True Perfection of a Servant is His Servitude\n\n'Excellent was the servant'—this is the greatest beauty of this great son, that he was an excellent servant. It should be kept in mind here that among all those wonders and extraordinaries of Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) with which books are filled, no mention has occurred here; if mention has occurred, it is of his perfect servitude. The primary beauty of a servant is that he becomes such a servant of his Lord that his Lord Himself testifies: 'excellent was the servant!' If this perfection is achieved, all other perfections are among its blessings, and if this is absent, even if someone achieves the signet ring of Solomon, it holds no value with Allah.\n\nThe Primary Beauty of Servitude is Devotion\n\n'indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah]' (Innahu awwab)—this very same attribute has passed above for Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) as well. That is, in this attribute, the son was the exact reflection of his father. The primary beauty of servitude lies in 'awwabiyyah' (turning to Allah)—meaning the servant's heart remains turned to God at every moment, and if ever any negligence occurs due to some reason, he falls before his Lord in such a way that the journey of years is traversed in minutes. Allah Almighty loves this very attitude of His servant. Whatever a person loses by sin, they gain far more than that from it if they repent with a sincere heart."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 31,
        "Tafseer": "\"When there were exhibited before him in the afternoon the poised [and] swift horses,\" (31)\n\nAn Example of Hazrat Sulaiman's Devotion\n\nJust as above, an example of Hazrat Dawud's (peace be upon him) devotion was described, this describes an example of Hazrat Sulaiman's devotion. First, understand the actual form of the event in simple words; after that, reflect on the individual parts of the discourse.\n\nFrom the words of the Qur'an, the form of the event that emerges is: one afternoon, a troop of noble horses was presented before Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) in the form of a parade for his inspection. The horses were numerous and the work was interesting; because of this, he became so engrossed in it that the sun set and the afternoon prayer (Asr) was missed. When he became aware of the prayer, he was so deeply remorseful of this accident that he could not control himself. He realized that this was the love of wealth in which he fell to remain negligent of the remembrance of God, and then he was so overcome by this state that he immediately ordered the horses to be brought back, and began to strike their necks and shins with the sword—as their love had become the cause of his negligence of God.\n\nThis is a state of being overcome by a feeling within which the motivation is highly noble; for this reason, in itself, this is a praiseworthy thing, but since in such states a person can exceed the correct moderate limits of the Shariah, this is not a precedent in religion. This is a specific state of the same nature as that in which Hazrat Umar fell upon hearing the news of the Prophet's (pbuh) death. Thus, when Hazrat Abu Bakr warned him in the light of the verses of the Qur'an, he regained his senses. It is possible that Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) also became aware himself or Allah Almighty warned him, though there is no mention of it in the Qur'an. Here, his action is mentioned to show his passion for repentance and devotion, and from this perspective, it is undoubtedly a magnificent event.\n\n'When there were exhibited before him in the afternoon the poised [and] swift horses'—'safinat' (poised) refers to those horses of noble breed that stand on three legs, raising the fourth; and 'jiyad' (swift) comes as a general attribute for good horses. That is, these horses were good in terms of their breed and also in terms of their attributes. In the Torah, the details of these horses of Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) are present.\n\n'And he said, \"Indeed, I gave preference to the love of good things over the remembrance of my Lord until the sun disappeared in the curtain [of darkness].\"' 'Ahbabtu' (I gave preference) here encompasses the meaning of turning away or negligence, and the preposition 'an' (over/from) is its indicator.\n\nThe referent of 'tawarat' (disappeared) is 'Al-Shams' (the sun), which is omitted here. In Arabic, for well-known and famous things, they bring the verb and the pronouns in this manner, and understand the referent from the context. Here, due to the word 'ashiyy' (afternoon), the context was clear; because of this, there was no need to mention the referent.\n\nThe Importance of Prayer in Religion\n\nBefore 'He said' (faqala), some words are omitted here due to contextual clarity—implying: he was so engrossed in the inspection of this parade that the Asr prayer was missed. Then, when he became aware, he said: 'I gave preference to the love of wealth over the remembrance of my Lord until the sun set and I remained deprived of the Asr prayer.' Obviously, he uttered this statement as an expression of grief and sorrow. Although these horses were horses of war and jihad, and the work in which he remained busy was also a work relating to jihad, since prayer holds the position of the primary foundation in religion, nothing other than necessity can be an excuse for negligence of it. We have discussed this in detail in its proper place.\n\nThe Asr Prayer Was Present with the Jews as Well\n\nFrom 'the remembrance of my Lord' (dhikri Rabbi), the context is proof that the Asr prayer is meant, because in the afternoon before sunset, only the Asr prayer can be performed. As for the question: was the Asr prayer present with the Jews? From this verse, it emerges that before sunset in the afternoon, there was some prayer with them as well. If its detail is not found in the Torah, it makes no difference, because the Qur'an has clearly charged them with the crime of destroying the prayer. These times of prayer which Islam has appointed are so natural and rational that the heart testifies that these very times of prayer were present in other religions as well, but the nations disputed regarding them and destroyed them.\n\nHere, remember also that regarding this very Asr prayer, the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions faced a trial on the Day of the Trench. Under the commentary of 'the middle prayer' (Al-Salat al-Wusta), we have pointed to some aspects of the importance of the Asr prayer.\n\n'\"Bring them back to me.\" Then he began to pass [his sword] over [their] shins and necks.' The referent of the object pronoun is 'Al-Safinat al-Jiyad', i.e., the horses. 'Mas-h' (passing/striking) is also known in the sense of killing, and 'mas-han' is for the emphasis of an omitted verb—meaning: 'yamsahu mas-han'.\n\nEvents of Being Overcome by a State are Not Precedents for Others\n\nThis points to that action of Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) which he took in that state of intense emotion and mofussilism. He immediately ordered these horses to be presented before him again. It seems that when the horses had returned to their stables, Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) was overcome by the realization that these horses had become the cause of his negligence of God; so he ordered them to be brought back, and began to strike their shins and necks with the sword. It clearly appears that this is a state of being overcome by a feeling; the word 'tafiqa' (began) points to this reality. From the verse, it is learned only that Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) struck some blows; it is not learned that he finished off all the horses, and doing so was also not possible because from the Torah, it is learned that the horses were in thousands. Probably, he struck some blows, and then became aware and desisted... Since this is a memorable event of his devotion and repentance, the Qur'an has mentioned it. Otherwise, this event is of the same nature as that which was committed by Hazrat Umar Farooq, to which we have pointed above. Events of being overcome by a state are not precedents for others; for this reason, those Sufis who have derived the permissibility of tearing garments from this have merely tried to find a Sufi point."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 32,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 33,
        "Tafseer": "Another Event of Hazrat Sulaiman's Repentance\n\nThis describes another event of Hazrat Sulaiman's repentance. Since the form of this event has also been made highly ugly in the commentaries, understand it first in simple words; after that, reflect on the words of the Qur'an.\n\nFrom history, it is learned that once Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) faced this severe trial: the enemies attacked and snatched most of his regions, and spread such disruption in the remaining regions that the administration of government was practically ruined completely. From their attacks, only the center was saved, in which Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) remained completely helpless and besieged. This was a trial from Allah Almighty, but Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) was a God-fearing king; because of this, he assumed that Allah Almighty had punished him for some lapse. This realization doubled his grief, and in this state of grief and helplessness, he remained on his throne as a lifeless body. At that time, he supplicated before his Lord with great humility: 'O Lord, forgive my sins, and though I have not remained deserving of Your favor and bounty, yet You are the Giver; therefore, despite my lack of entitlement, give me such a kingdom of which others, with such a lapse, are not and will not be deserving.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 34,
        "Tafseer": "Hazrat Sulaiman's Trial\n\n'And We certainly tried Solomon'—meaning We placed Solomon in a trial. This trial is a Sunnah of Allah. It is not necessary that Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) was placed in a trial as a punishment for some crime. Trials have been faced by all prophets and messengers, through which their patience or gratitude was tested. In a similar trial, Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) was also placed, and since he was a king, he faced this trial in the way of his kingship."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 35,
        "Tafseer": "Depicting Hazrat Sulaiman's Grief and Helplessness\n\n'and placed on his throne a body'—this is a highly brief but highly comprehensive description of this trial: we turned him from a powerful ruler of a vast kingdom into a completely lifeless body on his throne. The word 'jasad' (body) is used here as a metaphor to depict Hazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) helplessness and his grief. The meaning is: his kingdom was restricted to the center, and the conditions made him so helpless and grieved that only the body remained, as if the spirit had departed. Reflect on this, as there can be no better depiction of a helpless and grieved king, who is besieged in his center.\n\n'then he turned [to Us]'—meaning Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) did not despair of his Lord in such conditions, but realized that his grasp had occurred over some lapse of his. Thus, he turned to Him in repentance and seeking of forgiveness."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 36,
        "Tafseer": "Hazrat Sulaiman's Supplication and Its True Import\n\n'He said, \"My Lord, forgive me and grant me a kingdom such as will not belong to anyone after me. Indeed, You are the Giver.\"' This supplication does not mean: 'give me such a kingdom as no one else after me receives'; rather, his meaning was only: 'although due to my lapse, I have not remained worthy of any government, yet out of Your favor, give me such a kingdom of which neither I am deserving, nor anyone else after me will be.'\n\n'Indeed, You are the Giver'—meaning You are the Giver; therefore, despite my lapses, I am also hopeful that You will not keep me deprived.\n\nIn this supplication, the primary emphasis is not on the unparalleled greatness of the kingdom, but on being given the kingdom despite a lack of entitlement—implying: 'give me the kingdom despite my lapses when no one else after me will deserve it.' Within this supplication, the intense feeling of his lapse is proof of Hazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) extreme fear and repentance. God-fearing rulers have always attributed every calamity in their land to their own shortcomings. Regarding Hazrat Umar, it is narrated that during his time, once a famine occurred, which is famous by the name of 'Am al-Ramadah', and Hazrat Umar Farooq's state during this famine was such that he wet his beard with tears in his night prayers and supplicated: 'O Lord! Let not the Ummah of Muhammad be destroyed at my hands!'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 37,
        "Tafseer": "\"So We subjected to him the wind blowing by his command, gently, wherever he directed,\" (36)\n\nThis style of expression indicates that after the aforementioned trial, Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) received this special favor of Allah Almighty: He blessed him with such control over the wind as had not been achieved by anyone before him. In the commentaries of Surah Al-Anbiya and other Surahs, we have clarified that Hazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) navy was the greatest navy of its time, and his sailing ships were the most powerful ships of their time. The reason was that they had developed the sailing system to control the wind to such an extent that his ships made long journeys in every kind of sea, and their journey was hindered neither by the lack of wind nor by its intensity; they successfully faced even the most severe storms, and continued their journeys without any hindrance even in the absence of a favorable wind. Just as Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) had made his land power impregnable by developing the iron industry, Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) made his sea power unparalleled by developing the sailing system.\n\nHazrat Sulaiman's Control over the Wind\n\n'blowing by his command gently, wherever he directed'—'asaba' here is in the sense of directing to a target, just as 'asaba as-sahm' (hitting the target) is used—meaning whichever station they directed their ships to, they departed for it without any hindrance, without waiting for the season, because the wind was under their control. They made it favorable for their journey whenever they pleased."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 38,
        "Tafseer": "\"And the devils [of jinn] - every builder and diver, And others bound in shackles.\" (37-38)\n\nThe Science of Controlling the Jinn\n\nAlong with controlling the wind, Allah Almighty had also given Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) such knowledge through which he controlled the rebellious Jinn, employing them in construction works and also using them for diving to benefit from sea wealth. 'Devils' (Shayateen) refers here to the devils of the Jinn. This shows that Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) controlled only the rebellious Jinn, and did not interfere with the righteous ones. In 'every builder and diver' (kulla banna'in wa ghawwas), 'kull' (every) is for the emphasis of the attribute—meaning: they were highly expert builders and divers.\n\n'And others bound in shackles'—meaning another party of the Jinn was present with him bound in chains as a reserve force so that they could be employed as per requirement."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 39,
        "Tafseer": "\"[We said], 'This is Our gift, so grant or withhold without account.'\" (39)\n\n'without account' relates to 'This is Our gift'—meaning these great blessings are far beyond your estimation and assumption, and beyond your hopes and expectations. You could not even imagine them in your thoughts.\n\nCorrecting a Misconception of the Commentators\n\n'so grant or withhold' is an expression of that authority which every owner has in his property and every king in his kingdom. Its meaning is not: 'you may spend it on people or sit on it as a hoarder, you have the right to both'; rather, its meaning is: 'you possess full freedom and authority for both of these actions, but if you show generosity, you will fulfill its right and receive its reward, and if you become a hoarder, you will see your end with Allah Almighty Who has bestowed all this upon you.'\n\nThis is exactly what was said to Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him), which was said to Dhul-Qarnayn in these words:\n\n'We said, \"O Dhul-Qarnayn, either you punish [them] or else adopt among them [a way of] goodness.\"' (Al-Kahf: 86)\n\nThose who have derived from this verse the conclusion that Allah Almighty gave Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him) a license to do whatever he pleased and that there would be no accounting for him have misunderstood. Apart from other matters, have a look at the instruction given to his father Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) in verse 26 above, and then reflect on how the son could be given this free rein!"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 40,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 41,
        "Tafseer": "6. Subsequent Theme: Verses 41–64\n\nNext, to console the Prophet (pbuh), the mention of some Prophets (peace be upon them) has occurred who faced great trials but did not lose heart or despair; rather, they faced the situations with patience and resolve, turning to their Lord in their afflictions. Consequently, Allah Almighty removed all their afflictions and blessed them with His favor and bounty. Then, the conclusion is derived: with Allah, the best place of return is for His God-fearing servants. After this, the end of the God-fearing and the rebellious is clarified. Recite the verses.\n\n7. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nThe Trial of Hazrat Ayub\n\n'And remember Our servant Job, when he called to his Lord, \"Indeed, Satan has touched me with distress and torment.\"' (41)\n\nThe details of Hazrat Ayub's trial have passed in the commentary of Surah Al-Anbiya. Here, we will address only those matters that are specific to this Surah. The trials that a servant faces come by the command of Allah Almighty, but in their occurrence, a major agent is also Satan; for this reason, from the perspective of will and power, they are attributed to God, and from the perspective of cause, to Satan. From this perspective, Hazrat Ayub (peace be upon him) attributed his pain and torment to Satan. From the Book of Job, it is learned that Hazrat Ayub possessed great wealth and power, but was highly God-fearing and devout. Upon observing this state of his, Satan and his agents envied him and began to spread this propaganda against him: 'If Job is busy in God's worship day and night, what is his achievement? Since God has given him so much wealth and resources, if he does not worship, what else would he do? We would accept his virtue only if God snatches all these things from him and he still remains His devout worshipper!' Consequently, Allah Almighty deprived him of everything—he lost his wealth, his children, his companions, and his servants, but he did not despair in this great calamity; rather, he fell in prostration before his Lord and said: 'I was born naked from my mother's womb, and naked will I return to my Lord.' In the Book of Job, it is: after this, Allah Almighty said to Satan: 'Have you observed My servant, that after everything was snatched, he still remains mine?' Upon this, Satan said: 'That was the matter of wealth and children, so he observed patience; I would accept his virtue only if You afflict him with severe physical diseases and he still remains Your worshipper!' Thus, after this, he was afflicted with such severe physical diseases that reading their details in the Book of Job makes the heart tremble, but after this, his devotion to Allah increased even more, and in this trial as well, he defeated Satan. Following this defeat of Satan, Allah Almighty bestowed upon Hazrat Ayub far more than what was snatched from him.\n\nWe have presented this detail in the light of the Book of Job so that the correct aspect of Hazrat Ayub's supplication: 'Indeed, Satan has touched me with distress and torment' can be understood—showing what pains he had to suffer at the hands of Satan to prove his loyalty to his Lord in this world, and what a severe battle he fought with him.\n\n'Nush' means fatigue, pain, and calamity, and 'adhab' refers to those torments that he suffered in the form of physical disease; both words have summarized all those afflictions in which he was caught."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 42,
        "Tafseer": "\"[We said], 'Strike [the ground] with your foot; this is a [spring of] cool water for bathing and a drink.'\" (42)\n\nAllah's Favor upon Hazrat Ayub after the Trial\n\nAllah Almighty does not place His servant in a trial beyond a certain limit. Thus, when Hazrat Ayub's test was complete, his supplication was accepted immediately. He was instructed to strike a certain place with his foot, and a spring of water appeared there which was highly cool for bathing and for drinking. This was described as a cure for those skin diseases in which he was caught, and because of which his state was such that he sat on a heap of ashes day and night scratching his body with potsherds.\n\nStriking the ground with the foot to produce a spring is not a highly improbable thing. Near rivers and streams, beneath the upper surface of the ground, water veins remain hidden which appear immediately upon scratching with the hand or foot. Allah Almighty made some such vein a source of cure for Hazrat Ayub."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 43,
        "Tafseer": "\"And We granted him his family and a like [number] with them as a mercy from Us and a reminder for those of understanding.\" (43)\n\nAfter saving him from physical diseases, Allah Almighty also gave him his family members back, and with them a like number of companions and servants. During this period of trial, his family, children, and relatives had either left him or died. The servants and helpers had also scattered. Once the period of trial ended, the separated relatives gathered again, those who had died were replaced by Allah, and along with wealth, he received his servants and helpers back.\n\n'as a mercy from Us and a reminder for those of understanding'—meaning Allah Almighty did all this to show His favor upon His upright and loyal servant, and also to make this dealing of Allah a reminder for those of understanding.\n\nThere are several aspects of reminding in this for those of understanding. For example:\n\n* That Allah Almighty tests the loyalty of His servants, and success with Him is achieved only by those who remain steadfast in His test.\n\n* That a limit is appointed for this test with Allah, which is not exceeded.\n\n* That turning and devotion to Allah alone is the means of victory in this test."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 44,
        "Tafseer": "\"[We said], 'And take in your hand a bunch [of grass] and strike with it and do not break your oath.' Indeed, We found him patient, an excellent servant; indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah].\" (44)\n\nHazrat Ayub's Oath and His Exoneration from Its Responsibility\n\nDuring this period of trial, it seems, some such thought passed through Hazrat Ayub's mind which was contrary to patience and devotion to Allah; to punish his self for this, he swore an oath: 'I will strike myself with so many lashes.' The number of lashes is not mentioned. Although this covenant of Hazrat Ayub was the result of his fear and love of Allah, it is not permissible for servants to place themselves in a calamity, even if it is for the pleasure of God; because of this, Allah Almighty declared him exonerated from the responsibility of this oath. But since an oath holds great importance in religion, as it is the foundation of all covenants, he was instructed to take a bunch containing as many grass straws as the lashes he swore to strike and strike himself with it once—so that the oath was technically fulfilled, and no burden of breaking the oath remained on his heart.\n\nIn religion, this care is observed—that if complying with a command literally is difficult, complying with it in a symbolic form is necessary so that its memory is maintained. The instruction to perform Tayammum in the absence of water, and to pray by gestures in the absence of the capability to bow and prostrate, is based on this principle. An expiation (kaffarah) could also have been instructed, but at that time Hazrat Ayub (peace be upon him) was neither capable of paying a financial expiation nor a physical one—he had lost his wealth, and disease had made him so weak that he was not capable of fasting; because of this, Allah Almighty showed this special favor to him.\n\nCommentators have generally assumed that he had sworn to strike his wife with a hundred lashes, but there is no indication of this in the Qur'an, and the context is also against it. This is because traditions suggest that during this period of trial, his wife was the only one who served Hazrat Ayub day and night. Striking such a loyal wife is far from reason.\n\nJurists have also tried to derive the permissibility of legal loopholes (hila-e-shar'i) from this, but this is an independent subject. We will discuss it, if Allah wills, in its proper place. Here, limit the discussion to the context of the verse.\n\n'Indeed, We found him patient' indicates that in the whisper on which he swore the aforementioned oath, Satan tried to shake his patience, but he remained firm on the rock of patience.\n\n'excellent was the servant; indeed, he was one who repeatedly turned [to Allah]'—exactly these same words have passed above in the praise of Hazrat Sulaiman (peace be upon him). This highlights the shared objective of all these events, and clarifies the reality: to become an approved servant in the sight of Allah, it is not necessary that no mistake ever crosses a person's heart, but it is sufficient that when they feel a lapse, they immediately turn to their Lord and remain steadfast on the truth."
    },
