    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 48,
        "Tafseer": "\"And remember Ishmael, Elisha and Dhul-Kifl, and all are among the outstanding.\" (48)\n\nThe mention of Dhul-Kifl has passed in verse 85 of Surah Al-Anbiya. There, his mention occurred along with Hazrat Ismail and Hazrat Idris (peace be upon them), and the shared attribute of all these prophets was mentioned as patience. Here, in place of Hazrat Harun, the name is of 'Al-Yasa' (Elisha). There are two prophets in the Torah whose names resemble 'Al-Yasa'. First, Elisha, whose time is stated to be 713 BC; second, Isaiah, whose time is mentioned as 620 BC. Regarding Dhul-Kifl, we have presented our view in Surah Al-Anbiya. The context here too is of patience; though this attribute is shared by all prophets (peace be upon them), these prophets hold an eminent status in it."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 49,
        "Tafseer": "\"This is a reminder. And indeed, for the righteous is a good place of return,\" (49)\n\nSummary of the Discussion\n\nAfter narrating the events of the aforementioned Prophets (peace be upon them), the summary of the discussion is placed before us. It states that this is a reminder—meaning these are not merely stories of the past, but for you also, this is a lesson of advice, and a great lesson of advice; and remember that with God, a good place of return is for those who fear God alone, and for those who show arrogance upon hearing His advice and deny His Book, there is disgrace. To understand the sequence of the discourse, have a look at the first verse of the Surah.\n\nThe Reward of the God-Fearing\n\nThis describes that good place of return which was mentioned in the preceding verse with the words 'hasna ma'ab'. It states: for them will be gardens of eternity, whose gates will have been opened for them beforehand. Just as on the occasion of the arrival of an honored guest, the gate is opened beforehand to wait for him, similarly, the keepers of Paradise will be waiting for them to welcome them.\n\nBy 'drink' (sharab), beverages are meant. They will sit reclining on thrones in it, and will be demanding every kind of fruit and various beverages from their servants."
