    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 59,
        "Tafseer": "\"[Its leaders will say], 'This is a company bursting in with you. No welcome for them. Indeed, they are to burn in the Fire.'\" (59)\n\nThe Bickering of the People of Hell\n\nIn the preceding verse, the word 'Tagheen' (rebellious) is proof that this is the description of the leaders of disbelief. Now, it is stated that the crowd of their followers will also be brought before them, and they will be informed: 'These people are also going to enter Hell along with you.' They will immediately say: 'Let them be damned; they also are going to burn in Hell!'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 60,
        "Tafseer": "\"They will say, 'Rather, you - no welcome for you. You, you brought this upon us.' And wretched is the settlement.\" (60)\n\nThe followers will grind their teeth in anger and reply: 'Rather, you—no welcome for you; you are the ones who prepared this punishment for us.' In this phrase, reflect on the repetition of the subject ('antum') and the parenthetical clause between the two subjects. Anger is flowing from every single word. 'And wretched is the settlement' will come out of their tongues as an expression of regret—meaning: 'what a wretched settlement you prepared for us!' This sentence can also be a commentary from Allah Almighty, but there will not be much difference in the meaning."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 61,
        "Tafseer": "\"They will say, 'Our Lord, whoever brought this upon us - increase for him double punishment in the Fire.'\" (61)\n\nAfter this, they will supplicate before their Lord: 'O our Lord! Whoever prepared this punishment for us and led us astray to bring us to this station, increase for him double punishment in the Fire.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 62,
        "Tafseer": "\"And they will say, 'What is [wrong] with us that we do not see men whom we used to count among the worst? Did we take them [falsely] in mockery, or has [our] vision deviated from them?'\" (62-63)\n\nThen this question will arise within them: 'Where are those whom we used to count among the worst—declaring them as enemies of our ancestral religion, insults of our deities, and those who strike at our national unity? Did we mock them and declare them corrupters merely out of malice while they were among the righteous, or are they present here but we cannot see them?' This question will probably be asked by those who knew in the world that the Muslims whom their leaders targeted with criticism were good people, but due to being overawed by their leaders, they could not speak any word of goodness in their favor."
