    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 64,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, that is truth - the quarreling of the people of the Fire.\" (64)\n\n'That' (dhalika) points to 'the quarreling of the people of the Fire'. 'Takhacum' means mutual bickering and quarreling. It states: the bickering of the people of Hell of which mention was made is a real event; do not consider it a dream or a thought. Those who are leaders and followers of one another in opposing the truth today should do whatever they do keeping this end in view."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 65,
        "Tafseer": "8. Subsequent Theme: Verses 65–88\n\nNext are the concluding verses of the Surah. The Surah ends on the same theme with which it began, and we have pointed out in various Surahs this characteristic of the style of the Qur'an—that the theme with which the Surah began is also that on which it ends.\n\nFirst, the declaration is made through the tongue of the Prophet (pbuh): 'I am only a warner, warning you of a severe Day; when that Day comes, no one other than the One, Severe God will be of any use. My job is to warn, and I have done that. It is not my responsibility to force faith into people's hearts.' Those who are disputing with me out of pride and arrogance should remember that this is not the way of the Prophets and the righteous, but the way of Iblis and his followers, and they will face the same end which Allah Almighty had decided from the first day... Recite the verses.\n\n9. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n'Say, \"I am only a warner, and there is not any deity except Allah, the One, the Prevailing,\"' (65)\n\nWarning the Deniers\n\nThat is, warn them: 'I am only a warner, warning you of the coming time. Beyond this, I have no responsibility. If you remain firm on your stubbornness, you will see its end. If you are carefree regarding this Day relying on the intercessions of other deities, then open your ears and hear: there is no deity besides the One, Prevailing God.' The analysis of the word 'Qahhar' (Prevailing) has passed in its proper place. It means keeping everyone under His control—meaning He has kept His entire divinity under His control; He is not helpless such that He would stand in need of your deities to establish His sovereignty."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 38,
        "AyahNumber": 66,
        "Tafseer": "\"Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, the Exalted in Might, the Forgiving.\" (66)\n\nThere is No Room for Intercessors with God\n\nThis is an explanation of 'Al-Qahhar'—showing that He alone is the Lord of the heavens and the earth and all that is between them, and He is the Exalted in Might (Al-Aziz) and the Forgiving (Al-Ghaffar). 'Al-Aziz' means dominant over everything; it is impossible for anyone to escape from His grasp. At the same time, He is 'Al-Ghaffar'; therefore, for those who establish their entitlement to His mercy and forgiveness, He is highly Forgiving. There is no fear of any injustice or unfairness on His part such that the need for your assumed intercessors would arise."
    },
